			<div class="gallerytext">
<div style="text-align:left;"><b><a href="/wiki/David_Marr_(neuroscientist)" title="David Marr (neuroscientist)">David Courtnay Marr</a></b> (19 January 1945 – 17 November 1980) was a British <a href="/wiki/Neuroscientist" title="Neuroscientist">neuroscientist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Physiologist" class="mw-redirect" title="Physiologist">physiologist</a>. Marr integrated results from <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychology</a>, <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title="Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligence</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Neurophysiology" title="Neurophysiology">neurophysiology</a> into new models of <a href="/wiki/Visual_processing" title="Visual processing">visual processing</a>. His work was very influential in <a href="/wiki/Computational_neuroscience" title="Computational neuroscience">computational neuroscience</a> and led to a resurgence of interest in the discipline. <b><a href="/wiki/David_Marr_(neuroscientist)" title="David Marr (neuroscientist)">Read more...</a></b></div>
