			<div class="gallerytext">
<div style="text-align:left;"><b><a href="/wiki/Roger_Schank" title="Roger Schank">Roger Carl Schank</a></b> (born 1946) is an American <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title="Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligence</a> theorist, <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_psychology" title="Cognitive psychology">cognitive psychologist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Learning_sciences" title="Learning sciences">learning scientist</a>, educational reformer, and <a href="/wiki/Entrepreneur" class="mw-redirect" title="Entrepreneur">entrepreneur</a>.<br /><br />Beginning in the late 1960s, he pioneered <a href="/wiki/Conceptual_dependency_theory" title="Conceptual dependency theory">conceptual dependency theory</a> (within the context of <a href="/wiki/Natural_language_understanding" class="mw-redirect" title="Natural language understanding">natural language understanding</a>) and <a href="/wiki/Case-based_reasoning" title="Case-based reasoning">case-based reasoning</a>, both of which challenged <a href="/wiki/Cognitivism_(psychology)" title="Cognitivism (psychology)">cognitivist</a> views of memory and reasoning. <b><a href="/wiki/Roger_Schank" title="Roger Schank">Read more...</a></b></div>
			</div>
